NT: BE7A  OCA Tape #4. Hydrophones recorded on HiFi L & R. SMPTE code on Norm. Time Code available on tape #4. Radio station occurs occasionally, also, on HiFi Chs. This cut was made to show clearly the difference beteween the OTF clicks of the hydrophone and the clicks of the the whale.  It can be seen that they appear and sound very different, which is evidence to support the possibility that cut 97503OOS and 97703OOV really do show that killer whales can produce clicks and calls at the same time. Pulsed call?

NT: BE7A  OCA Tape #5. Hydrophones recorded on HiFi L & R. SMPTE code on Norm. Time Code available on tape #5. Radio station occurs occasionally, also, on HiFi Chs. This is a double uplooped and downlooped FM (two separate whistles), again very uncharacteristic of killer whales. Cannot be a Tursiops whistle since the whistles ovelap, and Tursiops cannot produce overlapping whistles. I originally thought that they may have been some attempt at mimicry, but the killer whale may indeed just be mimicing something in the pool such as a squeaking cable. So, one of the whistles may be a cable.
